Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the next innings! The players of Pakistan are out in the middle. Kieran Powell and Kraigg Brathwaite are the openers for West Indies. Mohammad Abbas to start the proceedings with the ball. Here we go...

West Indies will be looking to start strongly with the bat and end the day with wickets in hand. Jason Holder and Jayden Seales were the pick of the bowlers on Day 3 as they both ended with two wickets each. Roach had picked up three wickets on Day 1 but couldn't add to his tally and Alzarri Joseph continued to have a dry spell with the ball. West Indies took some time to clean up the tail and it's now up to their batters to make an impact. Stay tuned for the the second innings.

Pakistan will be pleased with how things turned out in the end. They lost three early wickets on Day 1 and had a slow start to the day 3 as well, but then the star man from Day 1, Fawad Alam came out and batted like he never left the crease. Alam stitched together important partnerships with the lower order batsmen, specially the partnership with Shaheen Afridi proved to be most fruitful. Alam remained unbeaten on 124 as Pakistan declared with 302 runs on the board. Pakistan will now be looking to get early wickets and gain further momentum.
Pakistan have declared on 302/9. Around 20-30 overs remaining in the day, Babar Azam might look at this as a decent score to post and ask the Windies batters to battle out.

A good session for West Indies. They have used the conditions well and made things happen. They didn't give away many wayward deliveries and held their lines too. Jayden Seales and Jason Holder were key in this session as they got the breakthroughs. Holder was the pick of the bowlers as he got back-to-back wickets and helped his team get back into the game. Now they would like to take the remaining two wickets quickly and wrap the things. Will they do it? Do join us for the final session.

Earlier it was Mohammad Rizwan and Faheem Ashraf who started the proceedings. Both were looking good in the middle but the latter gave away his wicket. Soon after the drinks break Rizwan went back and after that, it was all about Fawad Alam as he brought up his century in style. He is standing firm right now on 111 and will look to continue.
A productive session for the Windies as they have come back stronger in the latter part of the innings, despite a century from Fawad Alam.

PITCH REPORT - Samuel Badree says that some areas of the outfield are still damp. Jeffrey Dujon mentions that nothing much has changed from Day 1 and the pitch looks great for batting. He adds that it will be interesting when the new ball is taken because the new ball will bounce a bit extra which would be fruitful for the bowlers.

Joshua Da Silva is up for a chat, he says that it is very hot out there but they are all good to play. Says that he is happy doing the keeping. Adds that quick wickets are very important today. Says that he is feeling very good and he will do best for his team. Ends by saying that the first test win against Pakistan keeps a very special place in his heart.

Hello and welcome to Day 3 of the 2nd Test match between West Indies and Pakistan. Day 2 was unfortunately washed off and we couldn't get any play in, but we hope that Day 3 brings lot more action. Pakistan ended Day 1 on 212/4 which they would be pretty happy with after being 2/3 early on. Rizwan and Ashraf had both settled in before the end of play on Day 1 and Fawad Alam, who had to retire hurt due to cramps will also be raring to go. Kemar Roach was brilliant on Day 1 and he will be looking to give his team another fast start. Pakistan have three days in order to salvage the series, but will they? Stay tuned for a promising day of cricket. The first ball will be bowled at 9.30 am Local Time (2.30 pm GMT).

Right then! There are some revised timings for Day 3. The action continues on 22nd August 2021. The match will start early at 9.30 am Local (2.30 pm GMT), with 98 overs to be bowled. So do join us for the same. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Stay tuned for the official update and hope that we get some play today. The umpires have now decided that there will be another inspection at 3.45 pm Local Time (8.45 pm GMT).

After being put into bat, Pakistan were rocked early as they lost three top-order batsmen for just 2 runs. Kemar Roach and Jayden Seales were on song right from the start but then Babar Azam and Fawad Alam led the Pakistani fightback. Both notched up half centuries but then Alam got retired hurt due to cramp issues and Azam got out. Rizwan and Ashraf made sure they did not lose any further wickets and Pakistan ended the day strongly.

Hello and a warm welcome to the 2nd day’s play between West Indies and Pakistan. Pakistan are in a pole position as both Mohammad Rizwan and Faheem Ashraf are looking in good touch after losing Azam, this partnership has really built up. West Indies on the other hand are not too far away, they need quick wickets to get back into the game. Day 2 promises more exciting action. Will the Windies find the early breakthrough or Pakistan will build on their innings? We will find out soon.

That is all we have from the first day of the second Test. The action of Day 2 continues on 21st August 2021. It will start at 10.00 am Local (3.00 pm GMT). So do join us for the same. Till then, take care and goodbye!

The bowling was dominated by none other than Kemar Roach. He took two wickets at the top and also took the big wicket of Babar Azam later in the day. Jayden Seales was also good and took a wicket. While Jason Holder, Alzarri Joseph and Kyle Mayers did not take a wicket. But all of them with the exception of Alzarri Joseph were consistent in their line and lengths and kept things tight. Alzarri Joseph had an off day and was hit for runs. The second new ball is not too far away and West Indies would look to use that to rattle the Pakistani lower order in no time.

Pakistan had a very poor start with the bat. Imran Butt, Abid Ali and Azhar Ali fell very early and they were staring down the barrel. But Babar Azam and Fawad Alam showed great resilience to repair things for them. Both the batters made sure that they did not lose any more wickets in the first session and batted the entire second session. But after Tea, Fawad Alam started dealing with cramps and was unable to carry on and had to retire hurt. Babar Azam fell soon after and they were in some trouble. But Mohammad Rizwan and Faheem Ashraf put on a good stand to make sure that Pakistan do not slip further. These two would look to build further and Pakistan would want Fawad Alam to carry on once he gets to bat again.

West Indies wanted to go back to a pacer but the umpires denied it. So that will be stumps on Day 1. What a day this has been! Pakistan lost 3 big and quick wickets but would be very happy with where things stand at this point in time. They are well on track to put on a big score on the board.

While the first session was unfolding here, The Oval saw a momentous collapse in The Hundred Women's. Oval Invincibles Women managed to score 114 runs with the bat and Birmingham Phoenix Women were well on track to chase it down. At the 50-ball mark, they were 66 for 3 and would have backed themselves to chase it down with ease. But a 4-wicket haul by Tash Farrant turned the game on the head and Oval Invincibles Women won by 20 runs. They will now face Southern Brave Women on 21st August in the finale. In the men's clash, Southern Brave have opted to bowl first against Trent Rockets. The winner of this clash will face Birmingham Phoenix in the finale.

The hosts were destructive with the ball! Kemar Roach gave his team a dream start. He picked up two wickets in no time and without a doubt, he was also their pick of the bowlers for the first session. Jayden Seales, on seeing his bowling partner could not stay away from the spotlight and went onto snare a wicket to push Pakistan on the back foot. Other bowlers bowled really well, they probed good lines and lengths but were unable to get an edge into play. Overall, a very good performance by the bowlers, they will surely come back with the same intent in the session to follow. Do join us shortly to find out how the tourists will fight back and make inroads in this game. The second session is set to start at 12:40 pm Local (5:40 pm GMT).

A top-order collapse for the tourists! In the pre-match chat with Babar Azam, he had said that he would be happy to see off the new ball but that was not the case. The Pakistani top order was taken out in a jiffy. Abid Ali, Imran Butt and Azhar Ali were sent back in the first four overs and their combined score was just 2 runs. Babar Azam and Fawad Alam had a repair job to do and they did it successfully. They found some much-needed boundaries and did not play a lot of deliveries away from their body. They have steadied the ship with a crucial partnership of 60 runs. Pakistan would hope that these two would carry on post Lunch too.
What an engrossing session of Test cricket we just witnessed. The hosts would clearly be the happier side going into Lunch on Day 1. They have been very good with the ball so far.

The first session is set to begin. West Indies players stride out to the middle and take their respective fielding positions. Followed by the opening pair of Pakistan, Abid Ali and Imran Butt. Before the play starts, the players now go down on one knee to support the Black Lives Matter movement. They are up and the game is set to begin. Kemar Roach to start with the ball.
Nkrumah Bonner is down for a chat, he says that he looks to stick to the basics well. Adds that he wants to spend more time on the pitch and put a price on his wicket.

Imran Butt is down for a chat, he says he has been a good fielder since the start and he tries to work hard on it. Adds that fielding is very important to practice. Says that one has to back their ability and focus on the next ball.

Samuel Badree is down for the pitch report. He is joined by Jeff Dujon, who says that this pitch does not have as much moisture as the one for the first Test did and spin will play a part in this game. Ends by saying it won't be bad to bat first on this pitch.
Babar Azam says they will try to see off the new ball. Informs that Nauman Ali comes in for Yasir Shah. Adds that they practiced hard leading up to the Test and will look to perform better.

Kraigg Brathwaite is up for a chat. He says, they will bowl first. Goes onto say the pitch has a bit of moisture and will hope to use it wisely. Mentions there is one change as Alzarri Joseph comes in for Jomel Warrican. Adds they have quality spinners as well and his team is pretty balanced.

Pakistan (Playing XI) - Abid Ali, Imran Butt, Azhar Ali, Babar Azam (C), Fawad Alam, Mohammad Rizwan (WK), Faheem Ashraf, Nauman Ali (In for Yasir Shah), Hasan Ali, Mohammad Abbas, Shaheen Afridi.
TOSS - The coin goes up and it lands in the favour of West Indies. They have opted to bowl first.

Batting is an issue for both teams and that was evident in the first Test. Pakistan is heavily dependent on Babar Azam to perform with the blade in the hand. The Pakistani skipper delivers more often than not but Pakistan would want other batters to step up too. The story is the same for West Indies as they are dependent on Kraigg Brathwaite to score runs at the top. Brathwaite has been in great form in 2021 but the hosts would want others to perform too. Jermaine Blackwood played an important knock in the second innings of the first Test and the hosts would hope that other batters too pick up the responsibility of scoring runs.

Hello and a warm welcome to all! It is time for the second Test game between West Indies and Pakistan. The hosts currently have the momentum on their side, with a nail-biting victory in their last game. For a second it looked like we were in the middle of a limited-over match rather than a red-ball game. The Test format is really coming to life, the World Test Championship has surely has revived the energy in this format. This game should be yet another cracking encounter between the two. Stay tuned for toss and team updates.
The third innings is set to begin. The West Indies players stride out to the middle. Followed by Imran Butt and Abid Ali who walk out to open for Pakistan. Kemar Roach to start with the ball.

Right then. Pakistan have a handy lead of 152 runs. They will come out to bat and look to swell their lead. The West Indian bowlers have a huge task in front of them. They have to bundle out Pakistan for a low score, if they want to go on a hunt for a victory. Do join us in a short while for the third innings.

It was all about Shaheen Afridi! He started the proceedings for the visitors and ended it as well. He was surely the pick of the bowlers with 6 wickets to his name. Faheem Ashraf got a single wicket to his name. But it was a proud moment for Mohammad Abbas, who toiled hard and it paid off, as he ended up with three wickets. The Pakistani pacers never let the batters settle and left the hosts in an unpleasant situation.

The West Indies tail-enders could not hold the fort for long! Earlier, West Indies lost three early wickets in a jiffy and their top-order was destroyed. They were sent back with a disadvantage on Day 3, which continued to haunt them on Day 4. Bonner and Blackwood showed some signs of a fightback but it was not enough. They suffered another collapse in the middle order and were in all sorts of trouble. Holder gave them a positive start after Lunch and it looked like he was going to stay in the middle for long. But in no time, he fell out to Shaheen Afridi and all the West Indian hopes were shattered.

It did not take long for Pakistan to get rid of the tail-enders. Thanks to their main man with the ball Shaheen Afridi, who picked up 6 wickets in this innings, his best effort in a Test inning. Pakistan get a handy lead of 152 runs.

OUT! CAUGHT! West Indies have been bundled out for 150 runs! Babar Azam takes a stunning one-handed catch to dismiss Kemar Roach. Afridi pitches this one up, on middle. Roach goes for the big heave over mid-wicket but doesn't manage to clear Babar Azam, who jumps up and takes a beauty. Shaheen Afridi gets his sixth wicket and that's a career-best for him in an innings of a Test match.
Commentary.Howout: c Babar Azam b Shaheen Afridi

Commentary.Commentary: Length ball, straying down leg. Roach looks to pull hard but misses.
SIX! WOW! Banged in short, around middle. Roach stays back and dispatches it over the square leg fence.
Ali comes from the around the wicket to the left-hander and serves this one full outside off. Seales shoulders arms.
Full again, on off. Roach looks to cover drive but gets it off the inner half of the bat towards deep mid-wicket. They take one.
Full, on off and driven straight to mid off.
Length ball, on middle. Roach defends it on the leg side.
A quick bumper, on middle. Roach ducks under it.
On a length, around off. Roach plays it to covers.
Full and on the pads. Seales flicks it to mid-wicket.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! It is a 5-fer for Shaheen Afridi. What a game he is having. He has gotten Holder to depart, who was also the last hope for West Indies. A full-length ball, outside off. The ball nips away a bit. Holder stays back and looks to play the cover drive but mistimes it completely. The ball takes the outside edge and Mohammad Rizwan does the rest behind the wickets.
Commentary.Howout: c Mohammad Rizwan b Shaheen Afridi

Commentary.Commentary: Jayden Seales is the last man in for West Indies.
Angles in a length ball, onto the pads. Roach tucks it to deep square leg for a single. The umpire signals a no ball as the bowler oversteps.
A length ball, on off. Holder whips it through square leg for a single.
On a length and around off. Holder lifts it over the bowler's head. The ball goes towards long off. The batters take two.
Angles in a length ball, on off. Holder defends it back to the bowler.
A length ball, around off. The ball nips in a bit. Holder lets it go to the keeper.
Good length and outside off. Roach comes across and leaves it alone.
A full-length ball, on off. Roach defends it out solidly.
On a length, around off. Roach defends it to cover.
A length ball, on the bodyline. Holder stays back and tucks it to mid-wicket. They take one.
On off, pushed to cover.
SIX! All the way! You cannot ask for a more clean strike. A length ball, on off. Holder stands tall and powers it over the long on fence for a biggie.
A sharp bouncer on middle. Roach ducks under it.
Full length and just outside off. Roach looks to defend it out but gets beaten on the outside edge.

Review time. Pakistan have taken a review for a caught behind decision. The ball is close to the bat but UltraEdge confirms that the ball didn't take the outside edge. Pakistan lose another review and the onfield decision will stand.

NOT OUT! Another review goes in vain for Pakistan. Back-of-a-length ball, just outside off. Roach looks to defend it out but misses. The ball beats the outside edge. There was some noise insists Shaheen Afridi and Azam supports him by taking the review. The UlraEdge shows that the bat is absent. Kemar Roach survives.
Afridi fires in a short ball, just outside off. Roach leaves it alone for the keeper.
A touch short, on off. Roach stays back and defends it out awkwardly off the gloves.
Back of a length and around off. Roach though about ducking but he misjudges it completely. The ball nips in a bit and Roach gets hit near his armpits.
Who will bowl from the other end? It's going to be Shaheen Afridi. He has figures of 15-6-40-4 so far.
Good length and outside off. Holder shoulders his arms. A good start to the session for West Indies.
BEATEN! Back of a length, in the channel of uncertainty. Holder looks to have a poke at it but gets beaten.
A length ball, on off. Holder defends it out solidly.

FOUR! That is very impressive. Full length and just outside off. Holder hangs back and creams it through cover. The ball races away to the boundary. The second one of the over. Holder holds his pose as well, for the photographers.
Full and on off. Holder stays back and defends it out solidly.
FOUR! Delightful! A full-length ball, on off. Holder gets behind the line and drives it past mid on. The ball races away to the boundary. He has come out with some positive attitude.

The second session is set to begin. Pakistan players stride out to the middle. Followed by Jason Holder and Kemar Roach who come out to bat for West Indies. Mohammad Abbas to start with the ball. Holder to face.
...Day 4, Session 2...

So, luckily we had no rain interruptions and it was bright and sunny throughout the session. Hope it stays the same for the remainder of the day. Pakistan will be in a hurry to get rid of the tail-enders as soon as possible. But for how long can the West Indies remain solid defensively? To find out, join us for the second session at 1240 local (1740 GMT).

The pacers ran riot with the ball for the visitors! It was certain that it was a good batting pitch but the Pakistani bowlers thought otherwise. Shaheen Afridi started the proceedings of the day for Pakistan, he took an early wicket to get rid of the nightwatchman, Alzarri Joseph. But they could not capitalise on it quickly as there was a period when they gave away few runs. Later, it was Abbas who did the trick for the tourists by snaring two wickets in two deliveries. And before the end of the session, both Afridi and Abbas took a wicket each to add on to the opposition misery. Shaheen Afridi has 4 wickets under his name and Mohammad Abbas, the star of the session, with three wickets to his name.

A middle-order collapse for the hosts! West Indies did not start well, as they lost Joseph pretty early on. Then, it were Bonner and Blackwood who somehow managed to steady the ship, which brought in some ray of hope. But that was not the case, as when this partnership broke with Bonner being sent back no other batter could stick around for long. Mayers found his third nought of the series, he is yet to get off the mark. He will be disappointed with himself. And then just before Lunch, Blackwood and Da Silva got skittled out and the hosts were left in a miserable position. They still trail by 179 runs but with only two wickets in hand.
What an engrossing first session that was. Both teams fought hard to tilt the game in their favour but in the end, it is the visitors who will be the happier side coming into Lunch on Day 4.
Roach successfully negotiates the final delivery before Lunch. Length ball, angled in on middle and Roach keeps it out. The umpires call for Lunch on Day 4.
Afridi comes from around the wicket this time and serves a fuller delivery outside off. Roach makes a comfortable leave.
Full and wide, angling away from the right-hander. Roach leaves it alone.
Very full, around off. Roach jumps back to block it out.
Back of a length, around off. Holder turns it on the leg side for a run.
SIX! EDGY! Holder won't mind how the runs come. Shorter one banged in on middle and leg. Holder looks to pull but top-edges it and the ball flies over the keeper's head and over the fence.
Length ball, on off. Roach manages to keep it out.
Who will come out next? It is going to be Kemar Roach.

OUT! LBW! This time Joshua Da Silva has to depart! Peach of an inswinging delivery from Mohammad Abbas. This one pitches on a length around off and nips back in sharply. Da Silva looks to defend but gets caught on the crease and the ball raps him on the pads. The visitors all go up in unision and the umpire takes his time and deems it OUT! Joshua Da Silva reviews it again but the Ball Tracker shows that the ball would have gone on to hit middle of middle stump. Mohammad Rizwan has once again provided the breakthrough.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Mohammad Abbas

Commentary.Commentary: Review! Joshua Da Silva takes a review for LBW! The on-field decision is OUT. The UltraEdge confirms that the bat is absent. The Ball Tracker shows three reds. The ball is hitting the stumps. Joshua Da Silva has to depart. This time the review works against him.
Pitched up, on off. Da Silva blocks it out.

NOT OUT! Joshua Da Silva knew it straightaway that he didn't hit it and hence, took the review without any hesitation. Length ball, outside off and shaping away. Da Silva looks to defend but the ball goes past the outside edge. Delayed appeal from the visitors and the umpire gives it OUT! UltraEdge shows that there is a clear gap between bat and ball and hence the decision is overturned.

Review! It is players review for caught behind. The on-field decision is OUT. The UltraEdge shows that there is no spike as the ball passes the bat. The decision is overturned and Joshua Da Silva lives on. A good review taken by him.
Short but not short enough, on off. Holder pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Full, on off. Holder plays it to short mid on.
Fuller one, outside off. Da Silva goes for the expansive cover drive but once again inside-edges it onto the pads.
Pitched up, around off. Da Silva stays solid in defense.
Back of a length again, around off. Da Silva hops to defend but inside-edges it onto the pads.
Fullish ball, wide outside off. Da Silva leaves it alone.

Overthrows! Back of a length delivery, on off. Da Silva looks to defend but inside edges it towards square leg and sets off a for a quick single. Hasan Ali has a shy at the keeper's end and the fielder backing up fumbles to allow an extra run.
Angled in on the pads, from around the wicket. Da Silva looks to flick but misses it onto the pads.
A maiden for Abbas. Good length and outside off. The ball jags in after landing. Holder lets it go to the keeper.
Full and on off. Holder defends it off the front foot towards cover.
A full-length ball, on off. The ball nips in a bit. Holder hangs back and defends it back to the bowler.
Good-length ball and outside off. The ball moves away off the pitch. Holder stays back and looks to have a poke at it but misses. The ball beats the outside edge.
On a length and around off. Holder defends it out watchfully.
A length ball, on middle. The ball nips in a bit. Holder looks to flick it away but misses and gets hit high on his pads. Going down leg.
On a length and outside off. Joshua Da Silva leaves it alone for the keeper.
Afridi comes around the wicket now. He angles in a full-length ball, on off. Da Silva looks to defend it out but only manages to get an inside edge onto the pads.
Outside off, Da Silva leaves it alone.
FOUR! BEAUTIFUL! Back of a length and around off. Da Silva stays back and pushes it through point. The ball races away to the boundary.
Full and outside off. Da Silva drives it to cover but cannot find the gap.
Good length and outside off. Da Silva shoulders his arms.
On off, Holder blocks it out.
Just over the stumps, this one. On a length, this one lands just outside off and jags in a long way. Holder shouders his arms. The ball goes past over the off stump. A risky leave this one.
Good length and outside off. Holder leaves it alone.
A full-length ball, on the pads. Holder looks to flick it away but misses. Holder gets hit on his pads. Abbas appeals but the umpire is not interested. Going down leg.
BEATEN! On a length and just outside off. Holder looks to defend it out but misses. The ball beats the outside edge.
On off, Holder blocks it out solidly.
Joshua Da Silva comes out to bat with his team under pressure.

OUT! CAUGHT! Oh my word, Fawad Alam just came up with a beauty to get a hold of it. His stretch was top notch. Back of a length and around off. Blackwood looks to defend it out but only manages to get an outside edge. The ball takes off and flies to the right of Fawad Alam at gully. He runs that side and puts in a late dive to grab the ball comfortably. Suddenly, the game has shifted back in the favour of the tourists.
Commentary.Howout: c Fawad Alam b Shaheen Afridi

Commentary.Commentary: CLOSE! This one could've easily dragged onto the stumps. Back of a length and around off. Blackwood looks to defend it out. The ball takes the inside edge and bounces over the stumps.
Good-length ball, outside off, moving away. Blackwood prods and shoulders his arms.
Outside off, left alone by Blackwood.
FOUR! Up and over! A touch short, outside off. Blackwood lifts it over the slip cordon. The ball races away to the boundary.
Back of a length and outside off. Blackwood leaves it alone for the keeper.
Jason Holder comes in at number 8.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! At one point, Abbas was finding it difficult to take wickets. But now he has got two wickets in two deliveries. Mayers has to walk back with another naught to his name. Abbas comes around the wicket for the left-hander Kyle Mayers. Abbas serves it full and around off. Mayers looks to defend it out but the ball takes the outside edge and flies towards the keeper, Mohammad Rizwan who completes the job. Abbas will be on a hat trick when he starts his next over.
Commentary.Howout: c Mohammad Rizwan b Mohammad Abbas

Commentary.Commentary: Who will be the next man in? Kyle Mayers walks out to bat.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! For all the hard work Abbas has done, it gets paid off. He finally gets himself into the wickets column. This partnership was troubling the visitors a bit, but Abbas says leave it to me. He has done the trick for Pakistan. A full-length ball, on off. Bonner looks to defend it out but misjudges it. The ball moves away off the pitch and takes the outside edge. Mohammad Rizwan takes an easy grab behind the stumps.
Commentary.Howout: c Mohammad Rizwan b Mohammad Abbas

Commentary.Commentary: On a length and on off. Bonner squares up and defends it out.
Full and on the pads. Bonner tucks it short mid-wicket.
A length ball, on middle. Bonner stays inside the crease and defends it out watchfully.
A full-length ball, on the pads. Bonner flicks it to the right of short mid-wicket. Babar Azam dives to his right and makes a really good stop.

DRINKS! Bonner and Blackwood have steadied the ship for the hosts. Their partnership has passed the 60-run mark and they will hope to remain unscathed till Lunch. Pakistani bowlers have bowled well but have not found any success after the early breakthrough. They will be eager to chip away wickets and put the opposition under pressure.
Fullish ball, outside off. Blackwood shoulders arms to it.
Back of a length, on middle. Blackwood defends it to mid on.
Length ball, shaping away from outside off. Easy leave for Blackwood.
CLOSE! Afridi pitches this one up, just outside off and the ball straightens a bit. Blackwood looks to block but the ball whizzes past the outside edge.
Full and wide again. Bonner drives it towards covers and sets off for a quick single.
Starts with a fuller one, way outside off. Bonner lets it through to the keeper.
Shaheen Afridi is back into the attack now. His figures are 10-6-22-3 so far.
Back-of-a-length delivery, nips back in sharply from outside off. Blackwood hops on the back foot and manages to keep it out.
Length ball, on middle. Blackwood turns it to the leg side.
Shortish ball, outside off. Bonner taps it towards point and picks up a single.
Smart batting from Blackwood as he rotates strike immediately after the boundary. This one was on middle and Blackwood tucked it away to mid-wicket for a run.
FOUR! Deftly done by Blackwood. Abbas strays on the pads again and Blackwood tickles it down to the fine leg fence. 100 is up for the West Indies now.
Abbas starts with a loosener down leg. Blackwood looks to flick but misses.
Mohammad Abbas comes back into the attack now. His figures are 11-3-22-0 so far. He replaces Hasan Ali.

Ashraf brings out another false shot from Nkrumah Bonner. This one is pitched up, outside off and shaping in. Bonner doesn't move his feet and looks to drive but gets beaten inside the line once again.
Pitched up, around off. Bonner defends it out with ease.
BEATEN! Full and outside off, inviting the drive and Bonner falls for it. He misses the drive as the ball goes underneath the willow.
Length again, on top of off. Bonner defends it off the front foot.
A touch fuller, on that fifth stump line. Bonner shoulders arms to it.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone by Bonner.
Back of a length, nipping back in from around off. Blackwood hops and defends it on the leg side.
NO BALL! Full and straight. Blackwood defends it back to the bowler. A no ball is called for overstepping.
Shortish ball, on off. Bonner pulls it towards deep square leg for one.
Back of a length, on middle. Bonner stays solid in defense.
FIFTY partnership is up! Length ball, on middle and Blackwood nudges it sweetly through mid-wicket. The batters take three before the fielder cuts it off.
Shorter delivery, on middle and leg. Bonner pulls it behind square on the leg side for a single.
Full, on off. Bonner defends it out solidly.
Driven but without much timing. Full, outside off and Blackwood gets it off the toe end towards covers. End of a maiden over from Faheem Ashraf.
Length again, outside off and this one swings after going past the batter. Blackwood isn't going to offer a shot to it.
Blackwood defends the length ball on middle towards short mid on.
On a good length and on off. Blackwood punches it off the back foot to mid off.
Back of a length, outside off. Blackwood lets it through to the keeper.
Pitched up, on off. Blackwood puts out a stride to defend.
Good length and on off. Bonner defends it to cover.
Full-length ball, on off. Bonner prods and defends it to point. He yells a no straightaway for a single.
On off, Bonner defends it out solidly.

FOUR! Nicely played by Bonner. It was badly lined by Ali and Bonner took full advantage of it. A length ball, landing on middle and moving down leg. Bonner tickles it towards fine leg and finds the boundary.
A length ball, on off. Bonner defends it to mid-wicket.

FOUR LEG BYES! The runs continue to come for West Indies. Back of a length ball, on the pads. Bonner looks to flick it away but misses. The ball clips the thigh pads and goes towards fine leg. The ball ends up in the boundary.
FOUR! Great shot by Blackwood! Full and on the pads. Blackwood stays back and flicks it through square leg for a boundary.
Yorker length delivery, on middle and leg. Bonner stays back and successfully digs it out towards mid-wicket. They take one.
A length ball, on off. Bonner defends it out solidly.
Back of a length ball, outside off. Bonner has no stroke to offer.
Good length and outside off. Bonner lets it go to the keeper.

The umpires are checking the condition of the ball. The ball gauge is out and the umpires are not happy with the shape of the ball. Some used balls are now brought to the umpires to select from. A ball, similar in wear and tear to the one in use is chosen and play will resume now.
Full length and around off. Bonner stays back and blocks it out.
NO BALL! Full and on off. Bonner defends it out watchfully. The umpire signals a no ball as Ashraf oversteps.
BEATEN! Beautiful delivery by Ali to end the over. Good length and just outside off. Blackwood looks to defend it out but misses.

EDGY! FOUR! Much-needed boundary, no matter how the runs come though. A length ball, on off. Blackwood offers his bat to defend it out. The ball takes the outside edge and goes through the gap at the slips. The ball races away to the boundary at third man.

EDGED BUT SAFE! Back of a length ball, on off. Bonner is surprised by the bounce off the pitch. He looks to defend it out but does so with the shoulders of his blade. The ball flies over the slip cordon. The batters pick up an easy single.

Babar Azam has taken the review for an LBW decision. Ultra Edge confirms that there was no bat involved and Ball Tracker shows that the ball was going down leg. The onfield decision stays and Pakistan also lose a review.

NOT OUT! Pakistan lose a review here. Hasan Ali was sure about this one but it goes in vain. A length ball, on middle. The ball nips in a bit. Bonner stays back and looks to flick it away but misses. He gets hit on his pads. Ali pleads for an LBW but the umpire is unmoved. Hasan Ali wants his skipper to take it upstairs and Azam does so. The Ultra Edge shows the bat is absent. The Ball Tracker confirms the ball is missing the wickets by a long way. Bonner survives and the on-field decision stands.
NO BALL! A length ball, outside off. Bonner leaves it alone for the keeper. The umpire signals a no ball, as the bowler oversteps.

A loud appeal for LBW but turned down! Full and on the pads. Bonner stays back and looks to flick it away but misses. He gets rapped on his pads. Hasan Ali makes an appeal but the umpire says no. Going down leg.
Good length and outside off. Bonner lets it go to the keeper.
On a length and around off. Blackwood stays back and pushes it to cover.
A full-length ball, around middle. Blackwood nudges it to mid-wicket.
More runs! A length ball, on the pads. Blackwood flicks it to deep square leg. The batters pick two before the fielder cuts it off.
FOUR! CRUNCHED! Overpitched and on off. Blackwood offers full face of the bat and punches it past mid off. The ball races away to the boundary.
A length ball, on off. Blackwood stays back and defends it to cover.
Full and on the pads. Blackwood flicks it to mid-wicket.

DRINKS! Pakistan made a fast start as Shaheen Afridi got rid of the nighwatchman, Alzarri Joseph. Since then, Jermaine Blackwood and Nkrumah Bonner have kept the Pakistani pacers at bay. Any more wickets in this session will put the hosts on the back foot yet again.
Back of a length and outside off. Bonner stays back and pushes it to point but cannot find the gap this time around.

MISFIELD AND FOUR! Full and outside off. Bonner stays back and punches it to the right of point. Azhar Ali moves to his left but the ball goes through and ends up in the boundary. Good shot by Bonner, he has been very patient after getting a reality check early on.
Full and on middle. Bonner stays inside the crease and defends it to mid on.
Good length and outside off. Bonner shoulders his arms.
Fuller and on the fourth stump line. Bonner defends it out with ease.
NO BALL! A full-length ball, around off. Bonner defends it out watchfully. The umpire signals a no ball, as the bowler oversteps.
Ali starts with an outswinger. Full and just outside off. The ball nips away. Bonner lets it go to the keeper.
Hasan Ali comes into the attack. He replaces Mohammad Abbas.
Full and wide, Blackwood shoulders arms at it.
Back of a length, on middle. Blackwood goes back into the crease and defends it on the leg side.
Pitched up, outside off. Bonner squeezes it through point for a single.
Fullish delivery, around off. Bonner stays solid in defense.
Length ball, straying on the pads. Blackwood glances it towards backward square leg for a single. Appeal from the bowler but the umpire deems this as a run off the bat.
Starts right on the money does Ashraf. On a length and on off. Blackwood blocks it out to short mid on.
Faheem Ashraf is into the attack now. His figures are 2-2-0-1 so far. He replaces Shaheen Afridi.
Length ball, on middle. Bonner tucks it to mid-wicket.
Another one bowled into the channel of uncertainty. Bonner keeps on leaving outside off.
This one swung in late. Back of a length, around off and left alone by Bonner.
A touch fuller and on off. Bonner leans into the drive and gets it through covers for a couple of runs.
Length ball, on middle and shaping away slightly. Bonner gets behind the line to block it.
Pitched up, around off. Well left by Bonner.
Shorter ball, angled across and wide outside off. Blackwood shoulders arms at it.
On a good length, around off. Blackwood watchfully defends it out.
FOUR! Nicely timed by Jermaine Blackwood. Back of a length, and again on leg stump. Blackwood rocks back and tucks it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
FOUR LEG BYES! Afridi strays down the leg side again and pays the price. Blackwood looked to flick but the ball came off the pads and raced away into the fine leg fence.
Back of a length, on middle. Blocked out by Blackwood.

Down the leg side. Length ball, on leg stump and swinging further down leg. Blackwood looks to flick but the ball comes off the pads and through to the keeper. Appeal from the bowler but the umpire is unmoved.
Length ball, on off and nipping back in sharply. Bonner gets caught on the crease and the ball raps him on the pads. A bit too high and hence, no appeal.
Length ball, outside off. Blackwood plays it with soft hands towards point.
Outswinger, but a bit too wide to enforce a drive from Blackwood.
Full and wide, nipping away a bit. Bonner offers no shot to it.
Back of a length, on middle. Blackwood works it off the back foot towards mid-wicket for a single.
Length ball, on top of middle. Blackwood defends it on the leg side.

Excellent end to the over from Shaheen Afridi. Bowls this one on a length around middle and the ball shapes back in. Bonner looks to tuck on the leg side but gets hit high on the pads. Stifled appeal from the bowler but not given.
Swinging down the leg side. Bonner looks to glance it fine but misses.
This one is pushed wider on a length and easily left alone by Bonner.
On a good length and on middle. Bonner looks to block but gets it off the outside edge towards point.
This one is pitched up, around off. Bonner lets it through to the keeper.
Right on the money again from Afridi. Length ball, on middle. Bonner stays back and defends it out.
An inswinger to end the over! A length ball, on off, nipping in. Blackwood is upto the task and defends it out quite comfortably to mid on.
On a length and around off. Blackwood stays back and punches it to point but straight to the fielder.
A length ball, on off. Blackwood stays back and tucks it to mid-wicket off the inner half.
Full and on middle. Bonner tucks it to mid-wicket and takes off for a quick single.
JAFFA! Good length and around off. The ball moves away after pitching. Bonner looks to defend it out but misses. The ball beats the outside edge.
Blackwood is off the mark! Full and on the pads. Blackwood stays back and flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
This one was closer but not close enough to make the batsman play. Good length and outside off. Bonner leaves it alone without any hesitation.
On a length and outside off. The ball gets some bounce off the pitch. Bonner happily leaves it alone.
Full length and wide outside off. Bonner lets it go to the keeper.
Short ball, outside off. Bonner leaves it alone for the keeper.
LEG BYE! Back of a length and around the hips. Blackwood hops and looks to tuck it away but misses. The ball clips the thigh pad and rolls towards square leg. The batters collect a leg bye.
Jermaine Blackwood is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Don't worry says Shaheen Afridi and he strikes in his second over of the day. A length ball, around off. The ball is moving away from the right-hander. Joseph looks to defend it out but only gets an outside edge. This time though, the ball carries. Babar Azam takes a brilliant low catch at third slip. The nightwatchman has to depart. This is a bright start for the visitors and they will look to build on it.
Commentary.Howout: c Babar Azam b Shaheen Afridi

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length and outside off. The ball nips in a bit. But Bonner is still happy to leave anything outside off.
On a length and outside off. Bonner lets it go to the keeper.
Outside off, Bonner has no stroke to offer.
Good length and just outside off. Bonner leaves it alone.

EDGED BUT SHORT! Abbas could've found an early breakthrough but that was not the case, if Mohammad Rizwan had gone for it the scene could have been different. A length ball, on off. Bonner looks to defend it out but only manage to get an outside edge. The ball flies to the left of the first slip fielder, who get low to his left but gathers the ball on a bounce.
Fuller and on off. Bonner stays back and defends it onto the pitch.
Good length and outside off. The ball nips away a bit, Alzarri Joseph shoulders arms to it.
Outside off. Left alone by Joseph.
FOUR! What a shot! Full of confidence. Joseph is here to stay for long. A length ball, on off. Joseph punches it past mid off. The ball races away to the boundary.
A yorker and on middle. Bonner stays inside the crease and digs it out to mid-wicket. They take one.

LEG BYE! A full-length ball, on the leg stump. Joseph stays back and looks to flick it away but misses. The ball clips the pads and rolls to the leg side. The batters collect a single. Afridi and company make an appeal for LBW but the umpire is unmoved. Down the leg.
Afridi starts with a beauty! A full-length ball, outside off. The ball is moving away from the right-hander, Joseph looks to drive it away but misses.
Who will bowl from the other end? It's going to be Shaheen Afridi.
Good length and outside off. Bonner shoulders his arms.
A full-length ball, on middle and off. Bonner prods and defends it out.
A length ball, on the pads. Bonner stays back and tucks it to mid-wicket.
On a length and outside off. The ball moves away off the pitch. Bonner leaves it without any second thoughts.
Back of a length and around off. Bonner pushes it towards point but straight to the fielder.
Starts with a length ball, on off. Bonner stays back and blocks it out watchfully.
The first session is set to begin. Pakistan players stride out to the middle. Followed by Alzarri Joseph and Nkrumah Bonner who come out to bat for West Indies. Mohammad Abbas to start with the ball.

PITCH REPORT - Samuel Badree is up for the pitch report. He is alongside Jeff Dujon who says that nothing much has changed from yesterday and there are a few cracks. It is good pitch for batting and there are hardly any purchases for the spinners. It is a cloudless sky today and it should remain the same for long.

Waqar Younis, the bowling coach of Pakistan. He says his bowlers did really well in the first game and says they had a really good Test match the first one. Mentions Shaheen Afridi and Jaydon Seales are the future of cricket. He is really impressed by both of them and they are blossoming really well. Adds every session is important in Test cricket, also says if they get an early couple of wickets, the game is still on. Adds they will give their best shot. They have got the runs on the board as well. Ends by saying it should be a good day of cricket.

Are the rain gods coming back? The forecast says that there are showers and thunderstorms expected throughout the day. We have already lost 4 sessions in this Test match, if we lose anymore of the sessions it will be very hard to pull out a result. Although, the visitors can use these conditions to their advantage and barge through the West Indies batting line-up to get them near the finish line. Let us hope we get an uninterrupted game day.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 4 of the second Test match between West Indies and Pakistan. After Day 2 getting washed off and having just 1.2 overs of play in the first session on Day 3, we finally got some proper play in and it was filled with excitement. Pakistan declared on 302/9 on the back of an unbeaten century by Fawad Alam. Their decision turned out to be even better as Shaheen Afridi sent back the opening pair for West Indies and before the day ended, Roston Chase also fell. Pakistan look to be on top of proceedings and it'll be interesting to see how West Indies get back into this match. Stay tuned.

Earlier in the day, we once again had a stop-start, and play was halted before the second over of the day was completed. Eventually, after losing more than an entire session due to some wet patches around the bowling area, play resumed. The action took some time to spring into life but once it did, it was a riveting day of Test match cricket filled with ebbs and flows. The Test match seems nicely poised, with Pakistan having the upper hand. Day 4 will be crucial in deciding the match and the series as well.

That is all we have from the third day of the second Test. The action continues on 23rd August 2021 on Day 4. It will start at 9.30 am Local (2.30 pm GMT). So do join us for the same. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Fawad Alam is up for a chat, he says that the conditions were challenging. Says that after the start they had, they needed a good partnership and that is what he and Babar Azam did. Talking about the century, he is very happy to contribute to the team. Adds that his dad always motivates him. Talking about his celebration, he says that he copied from one of a Turkish series.

West Indies started the day on a strong note as Jayden Seales sent Ashraf back to the pavilion early on. Jason Holder then came back in and picked up two wickets in a row to put West Indies in pole position. Holder and Seales were impressive throughout the day, but the other bowlers struggled a bit. West Indies were put under pressure right from the start as they lost two wickets for just 9 runs. Before the day ended, Chase also fell, putting West Indies in quite a fix. Nkrumah Bonner has been the only positive with the bat and they'll be counting on him to carry on the good work tomorrow.

Pakistan will believe that they can get a result in this Test match. They did not have the best of starts on day 3 as Ashraf fell early and then Holder rocked them with two quick wickets. After that, Fawad Alam and Hasan Ali stitched together a partnership. The latter then got run out but Alam stayed determined. Shaheen Afridi provided great support to Alam, who went on to score an unbeaten century. The decision to declare was a fruitful one as the Pakistani bowlers did not disappoint, Shaheen Afridi rattled the West Indian top-order and set the tone nicely. In the end, they picked up three wickets and didn't give away many runs.

It was clearly an attack over defense approach from Pakistan when they came out to bat. Their opening pair, who are known for struggling a lot, batted extremely well, maybe because this time there was no pressure on them. West Indies fought hard and have snared three wickets but they have leaked away way too many runs than expected. They will look to come in and try to make things difficult for the visitors. Do join us at 1500 local (2000 GMT) for the final session of the day.

West Indies ended the session on a high! The West Indian tail did not last long as they got bulldozed by the Pakistani pacers. When they came out to bowl, West Indies did not expect such an aggressive start from the openers of Pakistan. Both their frontline pacers, Roach and Seales struggled with their lines and lengths and were hit for many boundaries. Alzarri Joseph, Kyle Mayers and Kraigg Braithwaite did manage to pick up a wicket each but West Indies will have to bowl much better if they are to restrict Pakistan from swelling their lead.

Pakistan have a lot of steam in their engine! Pakistan wrapped up things early with the ball after Lunch and then came out all guns blazing with the bat. The openers, Imran Butt and Abid Ali put the West Indies bowlers to the sword and were going more than run-a-ball as they put on 70 runs for the first wicket. Both of them fell in a span of four overs but Azhar Ali and Babar Azam, the two most experienced Pakistani batters were at the crease. But the former fell just before the Tea break. Pakistan go into Tea with a lead of 259 runs.

That is all we have from this series and we hope that you enjoyed our coverage. There is plenty of cricketing action coming in the near future and we hope you will join us for the same. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Babar Azam, the Pakistan skipper, says that it was a very important game as they lost the first game. Says that the partnership between him and Fawad Alam was very crucial. Adds that Shaheen Afridi was outstanding with the ball. Further adds that they wanted West Indies to bat around 20 overs on Day 4, which worked for them. Informs that they wanted to set a target around 330 for West Indies and they needed to be bold to level the series. Praises Nauman Ali for providing with 3 big wickets. Mentions that they wanted to play a spinner in this game as they felt that it would turn late in the game. About Shaheen Afridi, says that he is very young and is improving constantly.

Shaheen Afridi is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH and PLAYER OF THE SERIES. Shaheen Afridi starts by saying that it was a team effort and he is happy that he delivered for his team. He adds that it was tough because it was the last day and it was very hot. He adds that they knew when one wicket comes another one will soon follow. He also adds that all credit for his development goes to his brother and ends by saying that it was a very important win and happy to get on the board on the WTC points table.

Kraigg Brathwaite, the West Indies skipper, says that they were behind the game from the start. Adds that the batters need to work on the mindset as they are technically sound. Says that they need to find a way to get through the tough periods. Further adds that the team did a superb job in the first Test and the bowlers bowled really well in this game too. Says that they were not good in the first innings in this Test and that cost them. Praises Jayden Seales and says that he is a star in the making and he can get over 250 Test wickets. Praises Pakistan and says that they were very good as a bowling group.

Earlier in the Test, Pakistan were in big trouble at the start of Day 1 as they lost 3 wickets very early. But Babar Azam and Fawad Alam ensured that they recovered from that. The first innings was all about Alam as he went on to score a ton and made sure that his team got to a decent score. Despite Day 2 being washed out, the match remained exciting as late on Day 3, West Indies lost their top order and were behind the curve. It didn't take Pakistan too long to wrap things up on Day 4 and they had a big lead of 152 as the hosts crumbled for 150. The star of the show was Shaheen Afridi as he took 6 wickets in the first innings. Pakistan came out to bat with the sole intent of scoring quick runs and they did just that as they scored 176 runs at more than 6 runs per over. That meant that West Indies needed 329 runs to win the Test.

The stars for Pakistan in this innings were the two left-arm bowlers. Shaheen Afridi and Nauman Ali struck at the right time for the visitors and provided them with key breakthroughs. Shaheen Afridi took 4 wickets while Nauman Ali took 3 big ones. Hasan Ali was also very good in the first session and got 2 wickets. Afridi was sensational throughout the game and got 10 wickets in total.

West Indies had a big target to chase but they started decently. Kieran Powell and Kraigg Brathwaite were looking good but late on Day 4, Powell was run out. On Day 5 though, they had a collapse. In their top order, no one apart from Brathwaite and Jermaine Blackwood stayed out for long and both these two batters got out after getting starts. Kyle Mayers and Jason Holder did try to repair things but Mayers got out just before the rain break and they were in trouble. Holder and Joshua Da Silva stitched a decent stand, but Holder got out before the second new ball was available. That was the final nail in the coffin as the lower order crumbled.

A wonderful performance by Pakistan and they have deserved this victory. They lost the first Test by a whisker but have dominated this Test thoroughly. The hosts were outclassed and outplayed and barring that first hour on Day 1, they were never really on top of the game.

Pakistan were sensational with the ball. They once again kept things tight and bowled in the right channels. Shaheen Afridi started the day well and got the first wicket. Then, Hasan Ali was the one who provided two quick wickets to push them further to victory and right when a stand was building, it was Nauman Ali who broke it to put a cherry on top for them. They would now look to wrap things up as quickly as possible. Abid Ali did drop Kraigg Brathwaite but they need to be patient as a couple of more wickets means that they will have a go at the bowlers.

A really good session for Pakistan and they are inching closer to victory and to level the series. They needed early wickets and did find just that. Hello and a warm welcome to Day 5 of the second Test match between West Indies and Pakistan. With all three results still possible, we are in for an action-packed day of Test match cricket. 14 wickets fell in total on Day 4 and if that is anything to go by, West Indies will have to bat out of their skins today. Pakistan came out all guns blazing with the bat and declared at 176/6, setting West Indies a target of 329 runs. The opening pair for West Indies was going along nicely before an elementary mistake from Kieran Powell provided Pakistan with a lucky breakthrough. It will be an interesting contest and we'll have to wait and see which team shows more grit and determination as the series is on the line as well. Stay tuned for more updates.
... Day 5, Session 1 ...

Well, what an amazing day of Test cricket we witnessed. Also, luckily it was without any interruptions by the rain gods. Hopefully, it remains the same on Day 5. This game can go anywhere from this point. West Indies need 280 more runs to win, with 98 overs to be bowled, only if the weather permits. The visitors, on the other hand, have to hunt down 9 remaining wickets to level the series. Although they failed to find any movement from the surface in the final session, Pakistan would hope it changes on Day 5. We have a thrilling last day coming up for you all. Do join us at 0930 local (1430 GMT), as it is all to fight for on the final day. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Shaheen Afridi, is up for a chat. He says he just tried to bowl good lines and lengths which brought him early success. Goes onto say he got a good bowling partnership which helped him achieve his best figures in Test cricket. Mentions Test cricket is very difficult and all the teams do well in this format. Goes onto say he only aimed to take on the ball and it just got him a free run out. Ends by saying tomorrow is a big day and they will come out with an intent to fight and level the series.

Pakistan lost their heat with the ball in the final session of play but earlier in the day, they cleaned up West Indies quite easily to gain a 152-run lead. After that, the tourists were breathing fire with the bat right from the off. Imran Butt and Abid Ali were short of runs but they got them in the second innings in style. The opening stand of 70 runs set Pakistan on their way and everyone that followed chipped in with some quick runs. The skipper was the last man to get dismissed before declaring on 176/6 with a lead of 328 runs on the board. Pakistan tried to press the issue with the ball, but their pacers couldn't get much purchase in the final session. They got one breakthrough, which was a lucky one and they'll be looking for improvement on Day 5.

The fightback! West Indies' openers blunted the new ball really well. They did not repeat the same mistakes of their first innings. Kraigg Brathwaite and Kieran Powell were on their way to build a solid stand but it was an elementary mistake by the latter which gave the visitors a free breakthrough. It was then a tactical change of getting a nightwatchman into the game and it was Alzarri Joseph once again who came out to play that role. He did well to see off the day's play and the hosts would not be too disappointed with the way Day 4 ended.

Well, it is said that Day 3 is the moving day but in this game, it felt like Day 4 moved pretty quickly, also keeping in mind that Day 2 was completely washed out. West Indies would've loved to go back unscathed but it was not the case. Pakistan still hold the upper hand in this game, but a new day can bring up new challenges.

OUT! RUN OUT! Excellent from Shaheen Afridi and lazy work from Kieran Powell. Fuller delivery, outside off and driven nicely through covers. Afridi gives the chase and the batters come back for three. There is a shy at the keeper's end and it deflects off Rizwan's gloves to the stumps. They appeal and the third umpire is referred. Powell's bat is over the line but in the air, shows the replay. He will be distraught with himself because this is the last thing West Indies needed. Pakistan have a breakthrough now, a lucky one though.

DRINKS! West Indies have made a watchful start to the chase and they will be happy that they haven't lost a wicket. Pakistan have probed but their pacers haven't had the same kind of purchase from the conditions as they did earlier in the day. Will Pakistan be able to get a breakthrough or will West Indies safely see out the final passage of play on Day 4? We'll find out soon.
